  "prompt": "Can cataracts affect younger people? What are the most common causes of it?",
  "response": "Yes, cataracts can affect younger people, although they are most commonly associated with aging. In younger individuals, cataracts can develop due to a variety of factors:\n\n1. **Genetic Factors:** Congenital cataracts can be present at birth or develop during childhood due to genetic disorders or hereditary conditions.\n\n2. **Trauma:** An eye injury can lead to the development of cataracts. Trauma-induced cataracts can occur at any age following an eye injury.\n\n3. **Medical Conditions:** Certain medical conditions, such as diabetes, can increase the risk of developing cataracts at a younger age.\n\n4. **Medications:** Long-term use of corticosteroids is known to increase the risk of cataract formation.\n\n5. **Radiation Exposure:** Exposure to ionizing radiation, including X-rays and radiation from cancer treatments, can lead to cataracts.\n\n6. **Lifestyle Factors:** Smoking and excessive alcohol consumption are known risk factors. Additionally, poor nutrition and lack of antioxidant intake can contribute to cataract formation.\n\n7. **Eye Surgery or Inflammation:** Previous eye surgeries or chronic eye inflammation can also lead to cataract development.\n\n8. **Excessive Sun Exposure:** Overexposure to ultraviolet (UV) radiation from sunlight can increase the risk of cataracts, even in younger individuals.\n\nOverall, while cataracts are less common in younger people, they can still occur due to these factors. Early detection and management are important regardless of age to maintain good vision.",
